          "title": "The mutual dwelling — the *mone* inversion",
          "body": "The Greek word *mone* (dwelling place, abode) appears only twice in the entire New Testament, and both occurrences are in this chapter. At 14:2 the disciple has a *mone* in the Father's house — the heavenly, eschatological hope. At 14:23 the Father and Son make their *mone* with the obedient disciple — the present, experiential reality. The structure is breathtaking: the disciple's eternal home is in God; God's present home is in the disciple. The same word frames both halves of the chapter, and the obedient lover of Christ inhabits and is inhabited."
